title: Contributing to pdindicatoR
text: Fork package clone onto computer. haven’t done , recommend using usethis::create_from_github("b-cubed-eu/pdindicatoR", fork = TRUE). Install development dependencies devtools::install_dev_deps(), make sure package passes R CMD check running devtools::check(). R CMD check doesn’t pass cleanly, ’s good idea ask help continuing. Create Git branch pull request (PR). recommend using usethis::pr_init("brief-description--change"). Make changes, commit git, create PR running usethis::pr_push(), following prompts browser. title PR briefly describe change. body PR contain Fixes #issue-number. user-facing changes, add bullet top NEWS.md (.e. just first header). Follow style described https://style.tidyverse.org/news.html.

Version 0.0.2},   author = {Lissa Breugelmans and Maarten Trekels and Louise Hendrickx},   year = {2024},   url = {https://github.com/b-cubed-eu/pdindicatoR/},   abstract = {A package to calculate and produce a map of phylogenetic diversity scores for each grid cell in the input species occurences data cube, and calculate the percentage of high PD cells within currently protected areas. You provide a phylogenetic tree, the datacube for the corresponding species is downloaded from GBIF (or user-uploaded), and the package does the rest.},   keywords = {phylogenetic diversity; B-Cubed; biodiversity}, }

what: Calculate and visualize a phylogenetic diversity indicators based on species occurence data cubes
title: Calculate and visualize a phylogenetic diversity indicators based on species occurence data cubes
text: Phylogenetic diversity (PD) measure biodiversity takes evolution account. calculated sum lengths phylogenetic tree branches representing minimum tree-spanning path among group species. Phylogenetic diversity can used conservation planning maximise variety features, meaning aim conserve specific features, rather want boost diverse range features. Conserving variety features particularly useful light changing environmental conditions, can guess features important future. package, provide workflow calculate metric gives information well PD certain higher taxonomic group currently safeguarded protected areas spatial visualisation can used identify potential directions future expansion protected areas.

title: Calculate and visualize a phylogenetic diversity indicators based on species occurence data cubes
text: order start workflow, user specify filepaths phylogenetic tree, species data occurrence cube, two shapefiles: 1) grid, correspond grid used generate datacube 2) polygon shapefile boundaries protected areas. phylogenetic tree either nexus newick format. species occurrence cube must variable names example datacube (columns renamed loading). information obtain species occurrence cubes GBIF phylogenetic trees used package, refer vignette ‘Finding datasets use pdindicatoR’. following functions can used read datafiles:
code: tree_path <- "/path/to/mytree.tre"  cube_path <- "/path/to/mycube.csv" grid_path <- "/path/to/grid.shp"  # Read in newick or nexus format phylogenetic tree library(ape) tree <- ape::read.tree(tree_path)  # Read in species occurrence data cube. Use appropriate seperator! cube <- read.csv(cube_path, stringsAsFactors = FALSE, sep = "\t")   # Read in grid and protected areas shapefile grid <- sf::st_read(grid_filepath)

title: Calculate and visualize a phylogenetic diversity indicators based on species occurence data cubes
text: function generate_map_and_indicator() can used generate map visualizing phylogenetic diversity covering geographic area used generate occurrence cube.detailed maps desired, optional argument bbox_custom can used delineate bounding box. Coordinates desired geographic area can determined using https://epsg.io/ selecting CRS used grid.  optional parameter cutoff specified, value used classify cells high PD cells PD exceeds threshold value. indicator value calculated percentage high PD cell centerpoints fall within boundaries protected areas. result stored list, two maps first element (PD map high/low PD map) indicator value second element.
